  "bib_entries": {
    "147163373": {
      "title": "Emptying the nest and parental well-being: An analysis of national panel data",
      "abstract": "Panel data from a national random sample are used to investigate the effects of children leaving home on parental well-being. The \"empty nest\" is associated with significant improvements in marital happiness for all parents, regardless of parent's or children's characteristics. Overall life satisfaction improves significantly only under two conditions: when there is frequent contact with nonresident children or when there were young teens in the 1983 household. For both measures of parental well-being, the positive effects of the empty nest appear to be strongest immediately after the children leave. These findings, coupled with the high levels of post-launching contact, suggest that while parents experience a modest post-launch honeymoon, the parental role remains important to parental well-being."
    }
  },
